# DSFinalProject — Wildfire & Water Quality Analysis

## Setup Instructions (thanks claude)

### 1. Prerequisites
Make sure you have Python 3.10 or higher installed. You can check by running:
```bash
python3 --version
```
If you don't have Python, download it from https://www.python.org/downloads/

---

### 2. Clone the Repository
```bash
git clone https://github.com/yourusername/DSFinalProject.git
cd DSFinalProject
```
---

### 3. Create a Virtual Environment
A virtual environment keeps all the project dependencies isolated from the rest of your computer.
```bash
python3 -m venv .venv
```

Activate it:

**Mac/Linux:**
```bash
source .venv/bin/activate
```

**Windows:**
```bash
.venv\Scripts\activate
```

You should see `(.venv)` appear at the start of your terminal line. You will need to activate it every time you open a new terminal window.

---

### 4. Install Dependencies
With your virtual environment activated, run:
```bash
pip install pandas geopandas shapely pyogrio numpy matplotlib seaborn scikit-learn
```

Note: `csv`, `math`, and `statistics` are built into Python — you do not need to install them. you may need to use pip3 

---

### 5. Download the Fire Perimeters Data
This is the only file you need to download manually as it is too large to store in the repository.

1. Go to https://www.fire.ca.gov/what-we-do/fire-resource-assessment-program/fire-perimeters
2. Download the most recent Fire Perimeters geodatabase (.gdb)
3. Place the entire `.gdb` folder anywhere on your computer — your Desktop or Downloads folder works fine

---

### 6. Update the File Path
Open `ohyeahcode.py` and find this line inside `main()`:
```python
gdb_fires_path = "/Users/matthewkenville/Downloads/fire24_1.gdb"
```

Replace it with the path to wherever you saved the `.gdb` folder on your computer.

**Mac/Linux** — to find the path, drag the `.gdb` folder into your terminal window and it will paste the full path automatically.

**Windows** — right click the `.gdb` folder, select Properties, and copy the path from the Location field. Then add a backslash and the folder name to the end. Use forward slashes in the code:
```python
gdb_fires_path = "C:/Users/yourname/Downloads/fire24_1.gdb"
```

If your downloaded file has a different name than `fire24_1.gdb`, update the name to match. You can verify the layer names inside it by running:
```python
import pyogrio
print(pyogrio.list_layers("your/path/here.gdb"))
```

---